caption:
&quot;As the semester takes off, there's so many exciting things going on!! But we want to take a moment to slow down, take a beat, and honor the life of Dr. Carol Gill--scholar, disability advocate, and mentor--who passed away yesterday. Dr. Gill was a powerful voice for the existence and value of disability culture at UIC and across the world. We are so grateful for her legacy and disability ancestorship. 

From Dr. Carrie Sandahl, Interim Head of Disability and Human Development: 

&quot;Carol was a founder of disability studies not only in our department but nationally and internationally. She was a leader in the development of disability ethics and fiercely argued for the value of lives lived with disability.  Her work greatly impacted disability policy, disabled women’s health, and how we think and organize around disability identity and culture. We benefitted immeasurably from her scholarship, leadership, and friendship.&quot;

Dr. Gill started writing about and defining disability culture in the mid-1990s. She guest lectured and taught at UIC as an emeritus professor for a long while, and she's remembered for her kindness and the way she embodied disability culture values. From the day the DCC's doors opened, this quote has been on our walls in some way, shape or form: 

&quot;The elements of our culture include, certainly, our longstanding social oppression, but also our emerging art and humor, our piecing together of our history, our evolving language and symbols, our remarkably unified worldview, beliefs and values, and our strategies for surviving and thriving.&quot; 

Dr. Carol Gill, Rest in Power

ID: Rainbow gradient with a dark center with a quotation mark symbol and the above quote in white text. 

@idhduic @uicdiversity @uicahs&quot;.

